'''Mark Budz''' is an American science fiction writer, who co-wrote "[[Let Us Prey: The Whiphid's Tale]]" for ''[[Tales from Jabba's Palace]]'' with [[Marina Fitch]].

After graduating from the [[Wikipedia:University of Colorado|University of Colorado]] in [[1982]], Budz began writing full-time in the late 1980s. According to his official website, "Let Us Prey: The Whipid's Tale" still produces "enough royalties a year to buy a six-pack of expensive microbrew beer or bottle of cheap wine." His first novel, [[Wikipedia:Clade (novel)|''Clade'']], was published by [[Bantam Spectra]] in [[2003]], and was a finalist for the [[Wikipedia:Philip K. Dick Award|Philip K. Dick Memorial Award]]. It also won the second annual Norton Award for the best science fiction novel of the year set in the [[Wikipedia:San Francisco Bay Area|San Francisco Bay area]].<ref name="Bio" /> Later novels of Budz's include [[Wikipedia:Crache|''Crache'']] and [[Wikipedia:Idolon|''Idolon'']].

